summaries.title: Summary 284.1
summaries.summaryText: Aaliyah described how leading senior design teams strengthened her confidence in project management and technical problem-solving. She reflected on mentorship as a core component of her academic identity, often supporting younger women of color navigating engineering culture. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Summary 284.2
summaries.summaryText: Ethan noted that successful project outcomes often came from teams with diverse backgrounds and perspectives. He believes empathy and active listening should be core engineering competencies. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Summary 284.3
summaries.summaryText: Ethan discussed observing classmates who struggled to access tutoring or networking opportunities. His reflection on his own privilege as a continuing-generation student led him to advocate for more peer tutoring support and accessible design lab hours. [Part 2/4]

timelinePoints.eventDescription: Became lead designer on the robotics team, guiding a diverse group of underclassmen through competition preparation. [Timeline 4]
Co-founded a mentorship initiative within NSBE for first- and second-year engineering students. [Timeline 3]
Presented senior capstone project on sustainable urban drainage systems, earning department recognition. [Timeline 2]
Completed internship at a manufacturing firm where he recognized gender imbalance in leadership positions. [Timeline 3]
Joined the Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers during her first semester to find community and mentorship. [Timeline 1]

themes.title: Normalizing Mental Health Conversations in STEM
themes.description: Sarah’s work highlights the growing student-led shift toward wellness advocacy within rigorous majors. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Mentorship Networks as Retention Mechanisms
themes.description: Mentorship emerges as a consistent strategy for increasing belonging and persistence for students from marginalized groups. Aaliyah’s mentorship program demonstrates how peer-led initiatives can fill institutional gaps. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Acknowledging Structural Advantage and Allyship in STEM
themes.description: Ethan’s reflections underscore the role of allyship among students who recognize their positional privilege. He highlights how acknowledging systemic inequities can lead to more equitable classroom dynamics. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Navigating Institutional Barriers as a First-Generation Student
themes.description: First-generation identity shapes how Maria interprets bureaucratic and academic systems, creating additional cognitive and emotional labor compared to continuing-generation peers. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Peer Mentorship as a Belonging Intervention
themes.description: Daniel emphasized how structured mentorship programs provided psychological safety and belonging cues, normalizing struggle and improving persistence among marginalized students. [Extended 4]

quotes.quoteText: Seeing other Latina engineers at the SHPE conference made me feel like I’m not alone — like I really do belong in this field. [Context 2]
Sometimes I feel like everyone else just gets it — like I’m pretending to belong in these classes. [Context 3]
I wish there were a clearer path for first-gen students to find mentorship — it feels like everyone else already knows the rules. [Context 4]
My parents always say 'you represent the family'—it motivates me but also adds pressure. [Context 1]
Seeing other Latina engineers at the SHPE conference made me feel like I’m not alone — like I really do belong in this field. [Context 4]

areasForImprovement.title: Broaden Access to Early Engineering Exposure Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Ethan’s reflection highlights unequal early access to STEM exposure. Partnering with local schools and community programs can help level the playing field for underrepresented groups. [Extended 4]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Visibility of First-Gen Student Resources
areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students. Improving targeted outreach through orientation and department emails could reduce inequities in access to support. [Extended 2]

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Cultural Representation in Engineering Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Students emphasized the importance of seeing role models and mentors from similar cultural backgrounds. Faculty partnerships with student cultural organizations could foster inclusion and belonging. [Extended 2]
